# Aether Architecture

Aether is a modular app framework built on Nuxt 3 + Vue 3 + Vuetify 3 + TypeScript. This is NOT a traditional Nuxt app -- all functionality lives in feature modules, not in pages/ or components/.

**Tech stack**: Nuxt 3 (SPA/Electron), Vue 3 Composition API (`<script setup>`), Vuetify 3, TypeScript (required), Auth0 (automatic).

## Module Structure

```
features/my-feature/
├── index.ts         # Module definition (REQUIRED)
├── pages/           # Feature pages
├── components/      # Feature-specific components
├── composables/     # Feature logic
├── widgets/         # Embeddable widgets (optional)
└── README.md        # Documentation
```

Never put business logic in `pages/`, `components/`, or root composables. Those are for infrastructure only. Even home page content should be a feature module imported into `pages/index.vue`.

## Module Definition

Define modules with `defineFeatureModule()` from `~/composables/useModuleRegistry`. Key fields: `id`, `name`, `icon` (root level, not inside navigation), `routes`, `navigation` (use `title` not `label`), `setup()`, `onInstall()`, `onUninstall()`, `requires`, `provides`.

**Navigation gotcha**: If your module doesn't appear in the sidebar, check that `icon` is at root level (not inside `navigation`) and you're using `title` (not `label`).

See `patterns/module-definition.ts` for the full annotated template.

## Registration

Register modules in `plugins/01.module-registry.client.ts` (NOT in `app.vue`):

```typescript
import { defineNuxtPlugin } from '#app';
import { useModuleRegistry } from '~/composables/useModuleRegistry';
import myFeature from '~/features/my-feature';

export default defineNuxtPlugin(() => {
    const moduleRegistry = useModuleRegistry();
    moduleRegistry.register(myFeature);
});
```

## Event Bus

Always set up event listeners in module `setup()`, never in component lifecycle hooks (`onMounted`, etc.) -- components miss events that fire before they mount.

```typescript
setup() {
    const { on, emit } = useModuleBus('my-module');
    on('entity:selected', (data) => { /* always listening */ });
}
```

Event naming: use `feature:action` format (e.g. `entity:selected`, `news:updated`). Never use generic names like `update` or `click`.

## State Management

For state that persists across navigation, use `setup()`:

```typescript
setup() {
    const store = reactive({ selectedItems: [], isRunning: false });
    provide('myFeatureStore', store);
}
```

For cross-feature communication, use the event bus (above). For composables, return `readonly()` refs with explicit setters to prevent accidental mutation.

## Naming Conventions

- **Feature directories**: `kebab-case/`
- **Pages**: `kebab-case.vue`
- **Components**: `PascalCase.vue`
- **Composables**: `useCamelCase.ts`
- **Module definitions**: `index.ts`

## New Feature Checklist

- [ ] Created a feature doc in `design/` (copy `design/feature_template.md`)
- [ ] Created in `features/` directory with `index.ts` and `README.md`
- [ ] Uses `FeatureHeader` component (see ui rule)
- [ ] Declares `requires` and `provides`
- [ ] Registered in `plugins/01.module-registry.client.ts`
- [ ] Updated `DESIGN.md`
- [ ] Uses `markRaw()` for non-reactive objects in registry
- [ ] Cleans up in `onUnmounted()` / `onUninstall()`

## Debugging

- **Module not showing?** Check registration in plugins file, verify `navigation` object exists
- **Events not received?** Ensure listener is in module `setup()`, check event names match
- **State not persisting?** Use module `setup()`, not component state

## Using External Modules

Modules installed from npm/GitHub Packages expose widgets and composables:

```typescript
import { SomeWidget } from '@yourorg/some-module';
import { useSomeModule } from '@yourorg/some-module';
```

External modules are configured the same way as local ones -- register in `plugins/01.module-registry.client.ts`. See the module-workflows rule for install/publish details.

## Electron

The app can run as a standalone Electron desktop app. Use `useElectron()` to detect the environment and access platform APIs (window controls, persistent storage, app version). Build commands: `npm run electron:serve` (dev), `npm run electron:build` (production).

Runtime config in Electron must be changeable after packaging -- use `electron-store` for user-configurable values instead of `.env` files. Most setting changes require an app restart.
